article.headline: Charlotte has six players hit double figures

article.linkText: With depth, Charlotte puts a sting into Phoenix
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Tonya Edwards led six players in double
figures with 14 points as the Charlotte Sting beat the Phoenix
Mercury 90-68 Monday to remain unbeaten at home.

<photo1>

	   Kelly Miller and Andrea Stinson added 13 points, Tammy
Sutton-Brown and Allison Feaster each scored 12 and Erin Buescher
had 11 points and 11 rebounds for Charlotte (7-6), which is 6-0 at
home.

	   Washington is the only other WNBA team with a perfect home mark
at 7-0.

	   ''Being at home brings a lot of comfort for us,'' Feaster said.
''We don't have the large crowds that you see in Washington, but we
really feel the 6,000 fans that we do have.''

	   Jennifer Gillom scored 16 points for Phoenix (7-6), which was
outrebounded 41-23 as it dropped its second consecutive game and fell
to 0-4 on the road.

	   ''I told our team we aren't going to make the playoffs if we
don't play better defense than this,'' Mercury coach Linda Sharp
said.

	   The Sting shot 57 percent and made 11 of 19 3-pointers, one shy
of the team record set in an overtime victory against Los Angeles in
the season opener.

	   ''Our 3-point shooting really makes us dangerous,'' Sting coach
Anne Donovan said. ''We have a great post game, but when you start
the attack from the perimeter, it's tough to guard us.''

	   The Mercury missed all six 3-point attempts in the
first half and finished 1-for-13 for the game. The Sting outscored
the Mercury 12-2 over the final 4:25 of the first half to take a
47-32 lead.

	   Charlotte reeled off eight consecutive points early in the second
half to put it away. Dawn Staley's 3-point play made it 62-40 with
15:32 left.

	   ''It just didn't seem to matter what defense we were in, we just
couldn't get their momentum stopped,'' Sharp said. ''I want us to
have some kind of pride when we play defense. If I have to change
the whole lineup to get that, then that's what we have to do.''

	   NBA Hall of Famer Larry Bird watched the game from a first-row
seat on the baseline. As he walked to the tunnel at halftime, the
fans gave him a standing ovation.

	   Bird gave a basketball clinic to about 200 children at the
Charlotte Coliseum before the game. Bird is part of an ownership
group looking to bring an NBA expansion team to Charlotte to
replace the Hornets, who are moving to New Orleans.
